title: For Sale/Trade:  Model 1916 Berthier
postcontent: For sale (or trade for m1917 rifle) is a Model 1916 bolt action rifle from Fusile (Berthier). This Berthier rifle has a 32" barrel and is chambered in 8mm Lebel. This French Lebel rifle is fed by a 5-round enbloc clip (one included) and is in good condition for a rifle of its age. The bluing is aged and has minor surface pitting. The wood stock is heavily worn (the French beat these things up over the decades) yet the action is smooth and the base plate swings open easily. The bore is in good condition with clear rifling grooves. All serial numbers match on bolt, bolt head, trigger guard, and butt stock. "N" stamped on both barrel and receiver. These are hard to find in the US and there are no import markings. A great gun for anyone interested in World War One weapons or military history. US African American troops under French command would've had opportunity to use this arm along with its three-shot predecessor. More pictures available upon request. Must have SC license for local trade. Asking $400 or will trade for an m1917 rifle (can be WW2 rebarreled, not picky) or other World War One era gun. Let me know what you have. Thanks for viewing!

location: Highland Park, Minneapolis / St. Paul, Minnesota
postcontent: Daisy SOFT Air pistol-NOT airsoft.  There's a big difference.  Google it. Soft air guns were made for a short time- 1 1/2 years, 1986-87.  Its said they were discontinued because they were too realistic looking.  This one is modeled after a Smith & Wesson model 19 6" .357.  It functions very similiar to the real handgun, with this one you cock the "cartridges" with either of the two cocking tools.  Insert a small plastic "bullet" and then load the cartridge into the cyclinder.  Pull the trigger and the cyclinder rotates, when the hammer hits the "cartridge" the spring is released and it fires.  6 cartridges, 85 plastic pellets, the original operators instruction manual, and 2 Daisy soft air paper targets.  I've seen the instruction manual alone on EBay for $20.$125.00

title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant M91/30
postcontent: For Sale: A Russian Mosin Nagant M91/30 Rifle. As far as my research has gotten to me, this is an Izshvek (Izzy) factory rifle that came out sometime in 1927. This is important as in my research, production of the qualtiy of russian mosins dropped off percipitously after about 1928. The bore is near-pristine: no pitting, no marks and very shiny. Stock has few minor scuffs and dents, as to be expected from such an old rifle, but the stock finish and quality is remarkable, and is quite handsome. The rifle has been de-cosmolined as much as possible, but some may be present, however it has not effected my preformance with the rifle one bit, and there have been no instances of the infmanous mosin 'sticky bolt.'Rifle comes with milsurp nylon sling, and bayonet that i modified (it would not go on when initially purchased, so the inside of the bayonet was dremeled so it could fit.
